se on negotiated solutions</span><hr size=1> The raid scheduling situation we have here is a classic example of a solution where negotiation has broken down. In a complex mediation between lots of parties, this is not an uncommon situation. However, there are several points you should consider before posting your next &quot;I won't compromise, you are satan&quot; topics. <br>
<br>
1. Common interests- The reason that our reservation system has persisted for so long, where those on other servers have decayed into uberguild dictatorships, is that the guilds most capable of taking it that direction don't want to. They have their own reasons in each case, but it boils down to, we want to be able to schedule our lives and not spend every waking hour here to kill ubermobs. So, in this respect we have a common interest with the smaller guilds, who just want to insure that they retain a chance to kill mobs. Both want some kind of reservation system and were at one point willing to compromise with the other to make sure that happened. <br>
<br>
2. Best and worst alternatives to a negotiated solution-<br>
The worst alternative for the larger guilds is to continue to allow the current system to marginalize their interests. The Best alternative is to simply reduce the number of parties, work out a solution amongst themselves and exclude everyone else who stands in the way of their interests. They have the power to do this. Fortunately, the negotiated solution is far more attractive to either alternative, in this case, so a solution is possible. Keep in mind, their interests are in finding a solution that keeps a good reservation system in place. <br>
The worst alternative for the small guild/indy bargainer is that the larger guilds take matters into their own hands. the best is that the current system stays in place. In this case, there would be no reason to bargain, except that the larger guilds have the leverage of simply taking them out of the bargaining equation if they have to. Ironically, banding together to stop that would put them in the same position as the big guilds, and eliminate any need to bargain, since they would likely be willing to accept the same kind of system as the other big guilds at that point. The probability of the worst solution is far higher than the best for this party. Frustration will eventually drive SOMEONE to break the system. <br>
<br>
3. Interest based negotiation- So, keeping in mind the interests of the two parties, we must start again. No personal attacks, no &quot;your interests are bad, and I am pure as the driven snow&quot; posts. Bottom line, everyone has interests, all of them are reasonable. Adult people respect that and take advantage of it in their negotiations. There is a win/win situation here somewhere if we bother to find it rather than shooting everything down because its not exactly what we want. Compromise should be our watchword if we want the server to be anything else but just another server. <br>
<br>
Adun made one attempt to do this. A lot of people shot it down out of personal spite or a failure to compromise or recognize the interests of other parties. <br>
<br>
Instead, let me ask that if you don't like his proposal, make changes to it or propose your own. You can stand on your principals if you like, but consider the costs and the possible options. Consider the likelihood that you will actually prevail in the end, given that the server population increases daily, and the high level population is ballooning with people who have never heard and don't care about our reservation system, and will be looking at it from the standpoint of what it can do for them. <br>
<br>
Ultimately, there is an inevitable trend here, either we compromise, or we let it slide.  <p><A HREF="http://sr.amiga.tm/" TARGET="_new"><IMG ALT="Silent Redemption Member" BORDER=0 SRC="http://home1.gte.net/res007bh/ThoricPSD3_copy.gif"></A></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uretiredjustise.showPublicProfile?language=EN>RetiredJustise</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 59<br> <font color=#CC9900>(1/18/01 2:02:40 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.justise.com/j.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A general treatise on negotiated solutions</span><hr size=1> &quot;I won't compromise, you are satan&quot; topics. <br>
<br>
Perfect way of putting it.<br>
<br>
K here is my suggestion.<br>
<br>
We take everyone on the server that wants to go on plane raids, and sign them up in a database.<br>
<br>
Then we have 14 leaders sign up for 14 days, then we have a web page that goes through and selects the next say 4 clerics, 3 paladins, 3 warriors, 4 wizards, 3 enchanters, 4 mages, 4 necros, 4 bards.... ect.  That way everyone has a ready set fear raid with sufficent people and we make sure everyone gets to go. <br>
<br>
Don't like it? Want to raid with your friends you say? Well then you realize that person A who has more friends is going to raid more then person B right? <br>
<br>
The biggest problem all of you who are discussing this has is that none of you have decide whats wrong with the current system, except that &quot;the venril list is to long&quot;. How in gods name do you expect to come to an answer without a question?   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uadunofbrell.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Adun of Brell</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Burn the Witch!</span><br>  Posts: 856<br> <font color=#CC9900>(1/18/01 3:12:02 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.pangea.ca/~grinch/fenye.jpg width=92 height=150></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A general treatise on negotiated solutions</span><hr size=1> No, the problem with the VS system is that ANYONE can sign up for a rotation spot if they're indy, and ANY guild can sign up for a spot, regardless of size.<br>
